## 1. Competitive Landscape — what "enterprise-grade" actually looks like

Recovery/collections CRMs compete less on *features* (everyone has cases, payments, calls) and more on **operational trust**: does the tool feel like it was engineered by people who understand a collector's day, or does it feel like a CRUD admin panel with a logo?

What the best-in-class B2B dashboards (Salesforce Financial Services Cloud, HubSpot, Linear, Stripe Dashboard, Vercel, Zendesk, Intercom, banking-grade NBFC platforms) share structurally:

| Pattern | What it means in practice |
|---|---|
| **State survives navigation** | Filters, scroll position, selected tab, table sort — all restored exactly when the user comes back. This is non-negotiable per your brief and is a top-3 retention driver in operational tools. |
| **Optimistic, instant-feeling UI** | Clicking "assign" updates the row immediately; the network call reconciles silently in the background. Failure rolls back with a toast, not a page reload. |
| **Progressive disclosure of complexity** | A collector sees 5 things. An ops admin sees 40. Same codebase, different rendered surface — driven by RBAC + feature flags, not separate apps. |
| **Real engineering under the hood** | WebSocket-driven live counters (not polling every 5s), skeletons that match final layout pixel-for-pixel (no layout shift), keyboard-first power tools (Cmd+K), URL as the API for state. |
| **Trust signals** | Audit trails visible in-context, "who changed this and when" on hover, clear read-only vs. editable states rather than hiding buttons (see Section 4.4 on permission UX). |
| **Never a dead end** | Every empty state, every 403, every "no data" screen tells the user what to do next or who to ask. |

**What we will do better than typical collections CRMs (which tend to look like 2014 admin templates):**
1. A **manifest-driven UI** — the entire nav, dashboard widgets, and available actions for a tenant/role are described by a JSON config from the backend, not hardcoded per role. This is what lets us onboard a new NBFC client with a different workflow *without shipping new frontend code*.
2. **Permission-aware components by default** — every actionable element (button, menu item, field) is wrapped in a permission gate that either hides it, disables it with a tooltip ("Ask your Branch Manager"), or shows it — there is no fourth, ad-hoc state.
3. **State restoration as a platform primitive**, not a per-page hack — one hook (`usePersistedView`) that every list/table page uses for filters + scroll + sort + pagination, backed by URL params first, sessionStorage second.

