## 2. Core Architecture Decisions

### 2.1 Tech stack (confirmed + recommended additions)

| Layer | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Framework | React 18 + TypeScript (strict mode) | Given |
| Routing | React Router v6.4+ (data routers) | Given — use loaders for prefetch, not just component-level fetching |
| Server state / caching | **TanStack Query (React Query) v5** | Given — this owns all server data, caching, retries, background refetch |
| Client/UI state | **Zustand** | Given — session, UI toggles, tenant manifest, ephemeral state only. Never duplicate server data in Zustand. |
| URL state | **nuqs** | Type-safe, framework-agnostic (supports React Router) URL state manager. This is how filters, pagination, active tab, and sort survive navigation and are shareable/bookmarkable. Pairs cleanly with Zustand for state nuqs doesn't cover (e.g., scroll position, see 5.3). |
| Styling | Tailwind CSS + design tokens (Section 3) | Given |
| Component library | **Ant Design (AntD 5.x)** as the base component layer, themed via AntD's `ConfigProvider` + design tokens, Tailwind for layout/spacing utility only | AntD gives us production-grade Table, Form, Modal, DatePicker, Upload, Tree, Transfer out of the box — rebuilding these in raw Tailwind is a 6-month tax we don't need to pay. Tailwind stays for layout, spacing, one-off utility classes — **never** for reimplementing what AntD already does well. |
| Permissions engine | **CASL** (`@casl/ability` + `@casl/react`) | Isomorphic (same rules can run on backend Node/NestJS and frontend), TypeScript-native, supports `can()`/`cannot()` checks against subject+action+field, and scales from simple RBAC to attribute-based rules (e.g., "collector can edit case only if assigned to them and DPD < 90") without a rewrite. |
| Feature flags | **Unleash** (self-hosted or Unleash Cloud) | Open source, predictable per-seat pricing (not per-MAU), supports per-tenant/per-context targeting strategies, OpenFeature-compatible SDK, gives us kill-switches without redeploys. Alternative if budget allows a fully managed path: LaunchDarkly (stronger governance/SLA, materially higher cost at our scale). Recommendation: start on Unleash OSS self-hosted, revisit in Month 9 if we need enterprise governance features. |
| Real-time | **Socket.IO** (or native WebSocket + a thin reconnect/backoff wrapper) with a single app-level connection manager | For live notification counts, case updates, payment events. React Query's `queryClient.setQueryData` is updated directly from socket events instead of refetching — this is what makes updates feel instant rather than "next poll." |
| Forms | **React Hook Form + Zod** | Type-safe schema validation shared between form and API payload shape. |
| HTTP layer | Single `apiCaller.ts` (see Section 6) built on `axios` with interceptors | Centralizes base URL, auth headers, tenant header injection, error normalization, toast dispatch. |
| Auth | OAuth 2.0 / OIDC via a provider (Auth0, Keycloak, or WorkOS) + custom email/password + SSO (Google Workspace / Microsoft Entra ID for "sign in with company email") | See Section 7. |
| Toasts / notifications | AntD `notification` / `message` API, wrapped in our own `notify.ts` helper for consistent intelligent behavior (dedupe, severity mapping, action buttons, undo) | |
| Tables at scale | AntD Table + `@tanstack/react-virtual` for row virtualization on large datasets | Needed for the "infinite scroll / virtualized tables for large datasets" requirement — AntD's table alone will choke past a few thousand rows without virtualization. |
| Charts | Recharts (dashboards, funnels, aging buckets) | Lightweight, composable, good AntD visual pairing. |
| Testing | Vitest + React Testing Library + Playwright (E2E) | Not explicitly asked but required for a codebase multiple agents will touch — untested permission logic in a financial product is a liability. |
| Monorepo tooling | Turborepo or Nx, pnpm workspaces | If web + future mobile/admin surfaces are planned; otherwise a single Vite app is fine for Month 1–4. |

### 2.2 Why CASL over rolling our own RBAC

You asked specifically for a TypeScript package to manage roles/policies/permissions. CASL is the right call because:
- It expresses rules as `can(action, subject, conditions)` — this maps directly to your requirement ("collector can edit case IF assigned to them AND DPD < 90"), which plain role-string checks (`if (role === 'admin')`) cannot express without turning into unmaintainable spaghetti.
- It's **isomorphic** — the same ability rules (or rules derived from the same backend policy source) can be evaluated on the server for API enforcement and on the client for UI gating, keeping "hide the button" and "reject the request" in sync.
- `@casl/react` ships a `<Can>` component and `useAbility()` hook — exactly the primitive we need for Section 4.4 (permission-aware buttons).
- It avoids "role explosion" — the common failure mode where every new customer requirement spawns a new named role. We define **permissions**, and tenants assemble roles by composing permission sets on the backend (see 4.1).

### 2.3 Manifest-driven, multi-tenant frontend

The frontend never hardcodes "if tenant === X, show Y." Instead, on login (or tenant resolution via subdomain/custom domain), the backend returns a **Tenant Manifest**:

```ts
interface TenantManifest {
  tenantId: string;
  branding: {
    logoUrl: string;
    primaryColor: string;   // mapped into our design tokens, not raw override of every component
    productName: string;    // white-label support
  };
  featureFlags: Record<string, boolean>;         // resolved server-side via Unleash, per tenant+user context
  navigation: NavItem[];                          // ordered, role-filtered nav tree
  workflowConfig: {
    statusTransitions: WorkflowGraph;              // e.g., allowed case status transitions per org
    approvalRules: ApprovalRule[];
  };
  permissions: RawCaslRule[];                      // resolved for the current user, fed into CASL's ability builder
  locale: { language: string; currency: string; timezone: string };
}
```

This manifest is fetched once per session (cached in React Query with a long staleTime, invalidated on role/permission change via a socket event), stored in a Zustand `useTenantStore`, and is what every gated component, nav render, and feature-flag check reads from. **No component should ever import a hardcoded tenant ID or role name.**

