## 4. Roles, Permissions & the Manifest-Driven Nav

### 4.1 Permission model

Backend is the source of truth. Structure:

```
Organization (tenant)
 └─ Roles (tenant-defined, e.g., "Branch Collector", "Regional Manager" — names are tenant-customizable)
     └─ Permission Sets (our fixed vocabulary: case.view, case.edit, case.assign,
         case.delete, payment.record, payment.approve, settlement.propose,
         settlement.approve, report.export, user.manage, workflow.configure, ...)
         └─ Conditions (ABAC layer via CASL: ownership, branch scope, DPD range, amount threshold)
```

Tenants compose roles from our fixed permission vocabulary + conditions via an admin UI (Month 5 deliverable) — they don't get arbitrary code-level roles. This keeps the frontend permission surface bounded and testable.

### 4.2 Baseline roles (every tenant starts with these; tenants can rename/extend)

| Role | Sees | Can do | Cannot do |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Org Admin** | Everything across the org | User management, role/permission config, workflow builder, feature-flag visibility for their org, billing (if applicable), full audit log | Cross-tenant access (never, under any role) |
| **Branch / Regional Manager** | Their branch's cases, collectors, dashboards | Assign/reassign cases, approve settlements up to threshold, view team performance, escalate | Global org settings, other branches' data (unless explicitly scoped) |
| **Collector / Agent** | Only assigned cases, their own performance | Log calls/visits, record PTPs, request settlement (not approve), update contact attempts | Approve own settlements, see other collectors' cases, delete records |
| **Compliance / Auditor** | Read-only across scoped data + full audit trail | Export reports, flag anomalies, view every audit log entry | Edit any operational record |
| **Client / External Portal User** (if applicable) | Only their own case(s)/account | View balance, make payment, message assigned collector | See internal notes, other customers' data, internal workflow state |

### 4.3 Nav bar as manifest output

The sidebar renders directly from `manifest.navigation`, filtered at render time by `ability.can('view', navItem.subject)`. A nav item disappears entirely (not greyed out) if the role has zero access to that subject area — a collector never sees "Workflow Configuration" in the DOM at all, not even hidden via CSS (security-by-obscurity matters here: don't ship admin routes' data-fetching code paths to a collector's bundle either — use route-level code splitting keyed to permission groups).

### 4.4 Permission-aware component pattern (the "why can't I click this" problem, solved)

Every actionable element uses one shared primitive:

```tsx
<PermissionGate action="edit" subject="case" data={caseRecord}>
  <Button>Edit Case</Button>
</PermissionGate>
```

Behavior contract (this is the actual UX spec, not just code):
- **Allowed:** renders normally.
- **Not allowed, and the reason is role-based:** button renders **disabled**, not hidden, with a tooltip: *"You don't have edit rights for this. Contact your [Branch Manager / Org Admin] to request access."* — the bracketed role is dynamically resolved from the tenant's role hierarchy, so the user is told *who* to ask, not just "access denied."
- **Not allowed, and the feature is entirely unavailable for this tenant (feature flag off):** the element does not render at all — this is a packaging/entitlement boundary, not a permission boundary, and should never look like "ask someone" (there's no one to ask; the org hasn't purchased/enabled it).
- **Not allowed, and it's a genuinely hidden subject area (e.g., collector viewing another branch):** hidden entirely, same as nav — no information disclosure about the existence of the record.

This three-way distinction (disabled-with-reason vs. absent-flag vs. absent-scope) is what separates a professional permission UX from the generic "everything either shows or 403s" pattern most CRUD tools ship.

