## 7. Authentication & Security

- **Sign-in methods (Month 2–3 deliverable):**
  1. Email + password (with strong password policy, breach-check via HaveIBeenPwned range API at signup/reset).
  2. OAuth 2.0 / OIDC "Sign in with company email" — Google Workspace and Microsoft Entra ID as first-class SSO providers, since these cover the vast majority of enterprise/NBFC email domains.
  3. SAML SSO for large enterprise clients who require it (Month 6+, on-demand per contract — this is usually a sales-driven, not universal, requirement).
- **MFA:** TOTP-based 2FA (Section reference: "Two-factor authentication" from your feature list), enforceable **per tenant policy** (org admin can mandate MFA for all users).
- **Session management:** device/session list per user ("Device login history," from your reference doc), ability to revoke sessions remotely, IP-based login restriction as an optional org policy.
- **Recommendation:** don't hand-roll OAuth/OIDC. Use a managed identity provider (Auth0, WorkOS, or self-hosted Keycloak) behind our own login UI — this buys SOC2-relevant auth infrastructure, MFA, breach detection, and SSO connectors without building/maintaining them ourselves. WorkOS specifically is priced well for B2B SSO-per-tenant scenarios if enterprise SSO is a frequent client requirement.
- **Data masking:** PII fields (phone, ID numbers) masked by default in list views, revealed on explicit user action (logged in audit trail) — ties to your "Data masking for sensitive information" enterprise feature.

